  "articleSummary": "The article \"The Priority Trap\" critiques the misuse of rigid, fixed-priority dropdowns (e.g., P1-P4) in project management tools like Jira, arguing they lead to \"priority inflation\" and organizational chaos as teams endlessly add new levels (e.g., P0, P00) to falsely prioritize urgent tasks. It frames this as a failure to model the fluid, context-dependent nature of real-world priorities, which require dynamic, multidimensional systems (e.g., numerical scales, MoSCoW method) to reflect shifting goals and stakeholder needs. The tone blends analysis with dry humor, using metaphors like \"Engineering Theater\" and comparing priority inflation to CSS `z-index` wars to highlight systemic absurdity. Targeting software teams and project managers, it advocates for disciplined backlog hygiene, archiving obsolete tasks, and rejecting the illusion of control offered by static priority",
